We need to move away from a system that pits us against them and towards a system that creates unity.  The closer we can come to a system that is based upon consensus, the stronger and more effective we'll be as a nation.  That is the guiding principle behind IRV.  It's not about counting votes so much as it is trying to find the leader that best represents the will of the true majority.  No matter how you vote there are going to be multiple candidates that have platforms that you can get behind.  Right now you're only able to choose one, hopefully the one closest to your true ideal but often, because of the politcal climate, your one vote goes instead to the one you believe is most likely to win, or the one most likely to beat the candidate you despise. The way the system is set up right now ensures that the will of the minority is the one that is acted upon.  Anyone that did not vote for Bush in the last election is being ignored.  Over 50% of the voting populus did not vote for Bush, election fraud aside.  Over 80% of the population suppports reproductive choice and education yet our leaders continually try to restrict access to abortion and women's heath care, both here and abroad, and force abstinence only sex education down our throats.  Well over 50% of our population supports a stronger national heath care system, and yet our leaders continue to gouge away at it.  Over 50% of our population lives on under $50,000 a year yet our leaders do little to encourage economic growth that benefits anyone who makes under $200,000 a year.  <br>
If we move from the one vote system, the candidate that best represents the will of the true majority is much more likely to be the candidate who takes office.  If the objective of a democratic society is to have our leaders reflect the will of the majority then IRV is an option we must consider.  It's not the votes that matter, it's the representation that matters.  I have yet to find a system that gets us closer to representing the true will of the people than IRV. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bdrunkenphilosophy.showUserPublicProfile?gid=pavlovlocke>Pavlov Locke</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Drunken Philosopher</span><br>  Posts: 18<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/23/03 1:06:56 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fdrunkenphilosophyfrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Instant Run-off Voting</span><hr size=1> I'm sorry but you are just wrong.  &quot;IRV&quot; does not reflect the will of the majority any mroe than the current system does.  All it does it give a person more chances to vote against a particular person.  It doesn't provide any better means for the positive will of the majority to be accomplished.<br>
<br>
Of all those people you listed, did you figure out how many of them voted?  If people don't vote then they can't bitch about representation.  I am not an advocate of the current system by any means its messed up, but &quot;IRV&quot; is just the opposite side of the pendulum and therefore is not better.<br>
<br>
Why should we move to a system that we know is just as flawed as the current one?  And again why, should someone get their vote counted more than anyone else?  You say its not about getting votes counted its about the will of the majority, but counting votes is how that will is determined.  <br>
<br>
By all means let the winner(s) take all!<br>
<br>
In a demacracy the winners should take all because the winners will always be the majority.  The US unfortunately is not a true democracy we are a democratic republic which basically means that our votes guide the selection processes but the final say is out of our hands.  This is whre we need to change the system.  Not change the way votes are coutned so that the minority of people that vote gain tyranny through faulty vote counting.<br>
<br>
Locke <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bdrunkenphilosophy.showUserPublicProfile?gid=motherjones>motherjones</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/23/03 2:07:05 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fdrunkenphilosophyfrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Instant Run-off Voting</span><hr size=1> I was just talking to Twain and there's another way of looking at IRV and the way the votes are counted.<br>
Everyone still had the same amount of votes, expcet now it's 15 instead of 1.<br>
5 votes are awarded to your top pick<br>
4 to your second pick<br>
3 to your third pick<br>
2 to your fourth pick<br>
1 to your fifth pick.<br>
<br>
Add up the votes just the same way you do now.   Winner take all.<br>
<br>
I strongly disagree that in a democracy, run with our voting system, that the majority will always be the winner.  Just look at the percentages of voter from the last election.  52.72% of all voters who went to the polls and whose votes were counted did not vote for Bush.  <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.fec.gov/pubrec/fe2000/geparty.htm">www.fec.gov/pubrec/fe2000/geparty.htm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
in 1996 50.72% of the votes were not cast for Clinton.<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.fec.gov/pubrec/summ.htm">www.fec.gov/pubrec/summ.htm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
The way the system is set up ensures that the majority of people, who do vote, are not represented.  As for the issues above (reproductive access, health care, alleviating poverty) if we can assume that since these are key Green party and Democrat issues, and can assume that those voting G or D support them (which I think is very fair to say) then 51.12% of the population that voted in the 2000 elections supports the exact opposite of the current policy.  The one vote system does not ensure that the winner has a majority, all it ensures is a plurality, which is very different.<br>
<br>
And we don't know that IRV is just as flawed as the current system.  As of March 6, 2002 San Fransico has adopted IRV for it's statewide elections.  It's used for major elections in Australia, Ireland and Great Britain.  It saves money by eliminating the need for primary election, since the main function of a primary election is to narrow the field by eliminating the candidates with the least amount of votes.  IRV does this with out having to hold two seperate elections.  It's been shown in other countries to dramatically increase voter turnout, which makes the majority even clearer.  In no way does IRV promote the tyranny of the minority (please feel free to expound in detail 'cause right now I'm just not seeing it) it encourages the exact opposite.<br>
