<br>
-If there were 15 votes, 5-1st choice, 4-2nd choince..., then the votes would need to be stackable - make it so that you could vote Bush in all 5 slots. Otherwise it would give the non-R/D parties the advantage, as those voting for D or R with no second choice -- as these would be the most likely winners, at least in the beginning -- would lose 10 of their 15 votes. <br>
<br>
You could argue that anyone who voted for a minority party would lose more votes than that --(say Green - 1st choice, D - 2nd choice) -- they would only have four votes counted in the final election), but  at least they had a second choice that could be counted. <br>
<br>
-Locke, I don't see how you mean that it gives the minority a tyranny. Although I see potential for problems, I can see some benefit to it - imagine a town hall meeting where the townsfolk are discussing some important issue with more than two choices. <br>
<br>
One person may put a fairly radical idea on the floor, but it becomes obvious that this is not what most other people want. That person says, &quot;Okay, I can't have that, but I'll bend a little more towards the middle.&quot;<br>
<br>
Another person throws out another idea in the opposite extreme, and has the same response.<br>
<br>
In the end two choices are clearly popular; both near the middle, but on opposite sides. Those who had previously more extreme are willing to take one of the central views, so those are the two that are voted on in the end.<br>
<br>
So I can see how it could act more like a compromise/collective bargaining tool, and more people would be happy with their leader in the end.<br>
<br>
I can think of a slight variation of MoJo's 15 vote system that may work better:<br>
<br>
If you counted the votes in the way MoJo stated (1st - 5, 2nd - 4), you could throw out all but the final candidate being voted for.<br>
<br>
Say two ballots looked like this during the last election if it was run that way:<br>
<br>
1 - Nader (5)<br>
2 - Gore (4)<br>
3 - Lib (3)<br>
4 - Ref (2)<br>
5 - X (1)<br>
<br>
and<br>
<br>
1 - Bush (5)<br>
2 - Lib (4)<br>
3 - Ref (3)<br>
4 - X (2)<br>
5 - X (1)<br>
<br>
All but the final candidates with major chance of winning (Bush and Gore) would be thrown out, so in the end, the vote these two people are casting are NOT equal:<br>
<br>
Bush - 5 points, Gore - 4 points<br>
<br>
This would level out the playing field quite a bit more and seems to be a decent compromise, as only one vote counts and there's a penalty for secondary choices.<br>
<br>
People are still more likely to vote who they want in office, rather than just to beat the other major player, but at the same time they have less say progressively as they go down their rungs.<br>
<br>
On another point, I have to agree with Locke (and MoJo I think) - the electoral college needs to go first. This is the biggest source of our lack of choosing power.<br>
<br>
-Mills <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bdrunkenphilosophy.showUserPublicProfile?gid=pavlovlocke>Pavlov Locke</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Drunken Philosopher</span><br>  Posts: 19<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/23/03 12:18:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fdrunkenphilosophyfrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Instant Run-off Voting</span><hr size=1> The reason that IRV can lead to a tyranny of the minority is that it allows the people with the most extreme (and therefore least popular) views to get their votes counted more than once.  It would be like having rounds of election, where everyone that voted for one of the losers in the previous round got to vote again, but everyone who voted for one of the winners had to sit out that round.  <br>
<br>
I think that in a town hall meeting there is room for debate before the option is narrowed, what is the need to have IRV there?  The way that I see IRV, is that it becomes a who am I voting against issue rather than one in which I vote for the cadidate I think is best.  Thats what I mean by saying that it provides for the will of the majority in the negative sense.  We know that the majority of people did not want X to be in office.  That does not however mean that a majority of the people wante Y to be in office.<br>
<br>
As I said earlier our current system is very flawed!  That has more to do with the electoral college than to do with the way our votes are counted.  Further in 1996, Clinton had more votes than any other candidate so therefore he did hold the majority... simply because you can add up all the other candidate's votes and there are more of them does not mean that he didn't hold the majority.  In this last Presidential election we saw the glaring flaw of our current system, GW got less votes than Al Gore and still won the presidency.<br>
<br>
I really believe that before we try to change the whole way we vote we should correct our political system first.  The two party system is basically the kiss of death for the semblance of democracy that we have.  Eliminate political parties or make it so that no party recieves benefits in congress for having more people elected (I mean eliminate offices such as majority/minority leader).  This change would over time benefit the voters because we would see more people willing to vote for the right candidate instead of for the right party.  It would take time, but most true change does.<br>
<br>
Lastly, IRV is still an overcorrection and a misguided one at that.  The true problem with our system is the electoral college (why can't the voters make the decission themselves?) and the two party system (we shouldn't have to pick between the lesser of two evils just because they represent X party).  Perhaps true government funding for campaigns (perhaps no private funding and every candidate gets equal state sponsored time) without requiring that said cadidate's party did so well in the previous election.  So that if Nader Gore and Bush ran for president we would see an equal number of commercials for all three.  I just think that there are other things that need to be corrected first before we start changing the way we vote in America.  Without correcting the system we won't really accomplish much, it will still be D's and R's, instead of the best candidates (who might happen to be D's or R's).<br>
<br>
Locke<br>
