<br>
point by point...<br>
<!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:yellow;">The reason that IRV can lead to a tyranny of the minority is that it allows the people with the most extreme (and therefore least popular) views to get their votes counted more than once.  It would be like having rounds of election, where everyone that voted for one of <br>
the losers in the previous round got to vote again, but everyone who voted for one of the winners had to sit out that round</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--><br>
It is exactly like having rounds of elections.  Anyone that voted for the 'losing candidate' has to change their vote, but everyone that voted for a candidate still in the running has that vote counted again (traditional IRV not Twain's point system.)  Instead of giving those with the most extreme positions more votes, it pushes the votes to a less radical (and more popular) candidate.  It's like having five different primaries with out the cost or hassle of doing them independantly.  IRV also solves the problem of groupings of voters splitting their votes among similar candidates, which allows a candidate with only minority support to win.  Like the new D from Alaska who won because the third and fourth parties were more towards the radical  right and pulled votes away from Bush, who clearly had the majority support, just not the votes.<br>
<br>
IRV is used in many towns to elect leaders and to decide issues.  Not everyone can be in the twon hall meeting for a debate, so to better understand what the community wants you can put mulitple props. on the ballot.  Say you need to find a way to fund the local school district.  On the ballot are five propositions.  1 - Privatize all the schoools  2 - Sell exclusive rights and advertising to a cola company   3 - Raise property taxes   4 - Create a local income tax    5 - A combination of reformulating propery tax to a land tax, and a much smaller retail tax.<br>
So some of those are going to be really scary/really cool depending on your perspective.  With five options on the ballot it's not going to be easy to get a majority or even a plurality (because they are still different) using the traditional one vote system.  If you use IRV the one that wins will be the one that a majority of people can support.<br>
<br>
Clinton did not have the majority he had the plurality.  Majority means more than 50%, he didn't have it, granted it was much closer and it's possible for a candidate to get a true majority with the current system but it's much less likely.  Because of our current system we know that the majority of people didn't want x in office, but had we been using IRV we would have known what the majority DID what instead of having to essentially say, well screw them a plurality is good enough.   Because it's not good enough.  Even if we destroy the electoral college it's not good enough.<br>
<br>
I still don't see how IRV is an over correction, I can kinda see the shape of the arguement, but not the logic.<br>
<br>
Two party stuff......  IRV is the best way to beat the holy hell out of the 2 party system.  One of the key reasons why third (and fourth and fifth) parties have been so weak is the fear of slitting the vote, which occured in Arizona when a strong Green ran against a D, and gave the seat to an R with a 43% plurality.  Same thing in Alaska except the politics are reversed.  The fear of handing over power to their nemesis keeps people voting 2 party line.  IRV gets alternate paries in the door with out causing vote splitting.  All the sudden it's much easier for 3rd parties to get federal matching funds because they can hit the 5% mark(I'm still debating with myself how the fed. gov. should be funding elections)  All the sudden the 10% needed to be a part of the deabtes (which is also BS open up the debates for everyone) is also MUCH easier.  Their's no real opposition to IRV on a national scope, both the D's and R's support it as do all the third parties.  It would open up the feild very quickly. <p>Pray for the dead and fight like hell for the living. - Mother Jones</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bdrunkenphilosophy.showUserPublicProfile?gid=motherjones>motherjones</A> at: 1/23/03 1:45:43 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bdrunkenphilosophy.showUserPublicProfile?gid=motherjones>motherjones</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 19<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/23/03 3:32:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fdrunkenphilosophyfrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Instant Run-off Voting</span><hr size=1> On the third pary point Austrialia which uses a form of IRV results from 1996 (the most recent year available) for Calare<br>
