<br>
This is an over correction, because this is taking a problem where our votes do not count enough to where certain votes count too much!  In a democracy, majority rules.  (Do we really need to quibble over definitions?  Would you prefer Plurality which is in essence the same thing?)  Any change that we effect to take away from this, is a violation of democracy and is in effect usurping the power we all hold as individuals.  It does this, as I have said again and again, by not counting votes equally!  <br>
<br>
Perhaps IRV could save money, but that doesn't mean it is a good thing.  It doesn't mean its a democratic thing.  The statistics you gave from the Australian election are proof positive, as the &quot;losers&quot; got to vote more (in effect) it dramatically strengthened the eventual winners position.  I want to know why this is fair?  I want to know why these people got to vote twice (in effect) while the people who voted for him the first time... only voted once?  <br>
<br>
The simple fact that IRV would allow people to vote for more than one candidate in one election, means that people are allowed to vote more than once.  How is that reasonable?  Why should my vote be counted once and your vote be counted 5 times (for example)?  Or the other way around why should my vote be counted 5 times and yours once?  I know I sound like a broken record, but I want to know.  I want to know how this doesn't mean that the minority voters get more credit on their votes than the majority voters.<br>
<br>
Again this is an over correction, and misguided.  It won't even fix the problem.  And it leads to a situation where the minority begins to rule instead of the majority and then we are no longer democratic.<br>
<br>
