Exactly!  But that's not what happens because we base our system on plurality.  We have minor parties whose causes/policies are similar to the main candidates but because of vote splitting (like in Alaska and Arizona) the minority's causes/policies are the ones that are given power.  IRV puts the causes/policies that the majority support into power.<br>
And just cause I can, I take issue with calling our current system traditional voting, since 1 - just beacuse it's traditional doesn't make it just (ie electoral college) and 2 - IRV is just as traditional as the present system (not that it's age makes it just) it's been used in various incarnations in the US since 1912 in political elections and is used all over the US in institutional elections.   Even the Academy Awards uses STV (singel transferable vote) in determining their finalists. The American Political Science Association (APSA), the organization of political science professors, uses IRV to elect their national president, since political scientists understand that IRV is the fairest and simplest way to elect a single winner from a field of candidates.  Even Robert's Rules of Order supports using IRV to achieve a majority.<br>
<br>
And I take issue with saying that proponents of IRV are just pissed off wingers (left or right)who don't want to face the consequences of their vote.  Even if this were the case - which it's not - that does not make IRV inherently unjust.  It's supported by greens and libertarians, democrats and republicans, numerous social/political justice groups.  <br>
<br>
I've done some digging looking for critques or IRV ( because surely you couldn't be alone on this), and have still only been able to find one.  But it is very compelling, <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://electionmethods.org/IRVproblems.htm">electionmethods.org/IRVproblems.htm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
 especially when paired with their counter plan, Condorcet Voting.<br>
<br>
So now in the midst of things I will change my vision, Condorcet voting it is!  <br>
